PRINT

Python2

print 'This is a string'

Can use printf like syntax

x = 'String'
print 'Place my variable here $s' %(x)

# also works if x = 123. % formats variable as string

print 'Floating point number: %1.2f' %(13.145)

# %1.2f 1 is minimum number of digits before decimal. 2 if minimum after decimal. f means float. 

Using %25.2f causes python to print whitespace before number if number has less than 25 digits. 

%s - string format
%r - also converts to string but uses regular expression

print 'First %s, Second: %s, Third: %s' %('hi, 'two', 3)

print 'First: {x} Second {y}.format(x='inserted', y='two)

Python3

print('This is a string')

from __future__ import print_function

print('One: {x}'.format(x='INSERT!'))

